```java
import java.util.Arrays;

public class BinarySearch {
    public static int search(int[] arr, int key) {
        int left = 0;
        int right = arr.length - 1;

        while (left <= right) {
            int mid = (left + right) / 2;

            if (arr[mid] == key) {
                return mid;
            } else if (arr[mid] < key) {
                left = mid + 1;
            } else {
                right = mid - 1;
            }
        }

        return -1;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int[] arr = {1, 3, 5, 7, 9, 11};
        int key = 5;
        int index = search(arr, key);

        System.out.println("Element was found at index: " + index);
    }
}
```

This code defines a `search` method that takes an array of integers and a key to search for. It initializes two variables `left` and `right` as the bounds of the array. It then enters an infinite loop until it finds the desired element or reaches the end of the array.

In each iteration, the method checks if the middle element is equal to the key. If so, it returns the index of that element. If not, it updates the bounds based on the comparison of the middle element with the key and continues searching.

Note that this implementation assumes that the input array is sorted in ascending order. If the array is not sorted, you can use a sorting algorithm like insertion sort or merge sort to sort it first before searching.
